                            <p>

                                <br>
                                Chinatowns across America face a growing variety of challenges: Many have been  wiped away by gentrification and the constantly changing urban landscape.  Despite those facts, within Chicago’s bounds exists a still-flourishing Chinatown, one that remains a sanctuary for those seeking a home away from home.
                                <br> <br />
                                As you walk by the corners of Chinatown you will notice that everything is in some form of Chinese dialect and English. The town sustains itself by having businesses, restaurants, agencies, schools, and churches accessible to the community. At the same time from an outsider’s perspective, it provides the illusion of having traveled to another country. This keeps the influx of tourist constant while boosting the local economy. The red line stop leaves those eager to visit Chinatown in front of its impressive gate and Nine-Dragon Wall welcoming them to explore further and learn about its history. 
                                <br> <br />
                                Chinatown’s organizations are the relentless heart of the community. They balance tradition and progress by considering the opinions of each member of the community. A person does not just live in Chinatown, they are Chinatown. Each one unique, with their own dialect and story of how they came to be. It is a safe haven for those who need guidance and the opportunity to adapt to American culture. In it there are numerous job opportunities for the newly arrived and centers that offer the help immigrants often need to succeed. 
                                <br> <br />
                                Chinatown preserves its community by keeping itself separated from the outside world. Locals often advertise for jobs or housing opportunities in the streets rather than on the internet. This way those who live nearby will have an advantage over others. People rarely move out but if they do they try to be replaced by someone who would feel identified and supported by the community. Methods like this have increased the Asian population by 30 percent between the years 2000 and 2010.

                            </p>
								
